<m:mtr>
<m:mtd/>
<m:mtd>
            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
</m:mtd>
<m:mtd>       
     <m:msub>
              <m:mi>r</m:mi>
              <m:mn>1</m:mn>
            </m:msub>
            <m:msub>
              <m:mi>r</m:mi>
              <m:mn>2</m:mn>
            </m:msub>
            <m:msup>
              <m:mi>e</m:mi>
              <m:mrow>
                <m:mi>j</m:mi>
                <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                <m:msub>
                  <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
                  <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                </m:msub>
                <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                <m:msub>
                  <m:mi>θ</m:mi>
                  <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                </m:msub>
                <m:mo>)</m:mo>
              </m:mrow>
            </m:msup>
            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
        </m:mtd>
        </m:mtr>
      


</m:mtable>
</m:math>
      </equation>
      
      
      
      
      
      <para id="id2260773">We say that the magnitudes multiply and the angles add. As illustrated in
<link target-id="uid4"/>, the product <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:msub><m:mi>z</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> lies at the angle <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mo>(</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>+</m:mo><m:msub><m:mi>θ</m:mi><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:msub><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math>.</para>
      <figure id="uid4"><media id="uid4_media" alt="This cartesian graph contains three line segments extending from the origrin at different positive slopes. The upper line extends at the most positive slop to a point labeled z_1z_2. About three fourths of the way up this line there is the label r_1r_2. The middle line extends from the origin to a point labeled z_2. The bottom line extends from the origin to a point labeled z_1. From the x-axis to the middle of the upper line there is a curved line intesecting all of the previously mentioned line segments. The area of the curved line between the bottom and middle line segment is labeled θ_1+θ_2.">
